undrill","meanings":["Norman, English: nickname from Middle English * <i>jaunerel</i> ( <i>jaune</i> ‘yellow’ + suffix  <i>-erel</i>, of Anglo-Norman origin), for someone with a yellowish complexion, possibly suffering from jaundice. For the  <i>-d-</i>, compare the word  <i>jaundice</i>, from Old French  <i>jaunice</i>. The variant  <i>Jod(e)rell</i> may have arisen through misreading  <i>Jandrell</i> as * <i>Jaudrell</i>. Note William Jawdrell, 1448 in PROB 11, whose name may be an early form of  <i>Jodrell</i> or a misreading of  <i>Jaundrell</i>."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Agnes Jodrell was born in 1469, in Derby, Derbyshire, England, her father, George Jodrell of Derbyshire, was 15 and her mother, Caroline Matilda Sutton-Dudley, was 12. She married Thomas Masterson of Nantwich about 1488, in Worleston, Cheshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1523, in Nantwich, Cheshire, England, at the age of 54."},"et":{"1469–1523":"1469–1523","1465–1513":"1465–1513","1491–Male":"1491–Surnud","1495–1551":"1495–1551","1504–1548":"1504–1548","1454–Male":"1454–Surnud","1457–Fema